re": 1}], "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Podocarpus excelsus improperly are inducing nausea and causing diarrhea due to the plant's toxic compounds, such as podocarpic acid and podophyllotoxin, which can cause gastrointestinal irritation and disrupt normal digestion. This is because the plant's toxic compounds can affect the gut's lining and alter the balance of gut flora, leading to nausea and diarrhea in some individuals. Additionally, Podocarpus excelsus can interact with certain medications, such as blood thinners and diabetes medications, by altering their metabolism and potency, which can exacerbate underlying health conditions. Furthermore, improper use of the plant can lead to more severe side effects, including vomiting, abdominal pain, and bloody stools, especially in individuals with pre-existing liver or kidney disease. Prolonged exposure to the plant's toxic compounds can also cause liver damage and kidney failure if not properly monitored and treated.", "family_slug": "podocarpaceae", "family_name": "Podocarpaceae", "what_description": "Podocarpus excelsus is a species of evergreen tree belonging to the family Podocarpaceae. It is native to the tropical forests of southern Africa, specifically in South Africa, Lesotho, and Swaziland. Botanically, it is characterized by its conical shape, straight trunk, and smooth, greyish-brown bark. The tree grows up to 30 meters in height, with a broad, rounded crown and needle-like leaves that are 1-3 centimeters long and arranged in two rows along the branch. The leaves have a distinctive blue-green color and are highly aromatic, with a distinctive scent when crushed.", "uses": "Podocarpus excelsus, commonly known as the yellowwood, has been used in traditional medicine for various purposes. Its bark and leaves are said to have anti-inflammatory and antiseptic properties, which have been used to treat wounds and skin conditions. In some cultures, the plant's extracts are used to treat fever and respiratory issues. Additionally, the yellowwood's leaves and bark are believed to have antimicrobial properties, making them effective against certain bacterial and fungal infections. Further research is needed to confirm the effectiveness and safety of these medicinal uses.", "taxonomy": "Podocarpus excelsus is classified as a species of evergreen coniferous tree, belonging to the family Podocarpaceae. This family is a part of the broader gymnosperm group, consisting of coniferous trees and shrubs. Within the family Podocarpaceae, Podocarpus excelsus is placed in the genus Podocarpus, which comprises around 101 species of conifers. The genus Podocarpus is further grouped into the order Coniferales and class Pinopsida. Podocarpus excelsus is also categorized as a member of the phylum Pinophyta.", "benefits": "Podocarpus excelsus is known to have various health benefits, particularly in traditional medicine. The plant's extracts have been used to treat various conditions, including fever, rheumatism, and respiratory issues. It is also said to have antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties, which can help protect against cell damage and reduce inflammation. The plant's leaves and bark are often used in teas and infusions to promote relaxation and improve overall well-being. Further research is needed to confirm the full extent of Podocarpus excelsus's health benefits.", "parts": "Podocarpus excelsus is a species of coniferous tree native to South Africa, and like many other members of the Podocarpaceae family, it has been studied for its potential medicinal properties. The heartwood and resin of Podocarpus excelsus have been used in traditional medicine to treat a variety of ailments, including fever, rheumatism, and skin conditions. The plant's essential oils have been found to exhibit antimicrobial and anti-inflammatory properties, which may contribute to its medicinal uses. The heartwood has also been found to contain compounds with potential anti-cancer properties. Further research is needed to fully understand the medicinal potential of Podocarpus excelsus.", "intro": "Podocarpus excelsus, also known as Yellowwood or Real Yellowwood, is a coniferous tree species native to the subtropical regions of southern Africa. The health benefits of Podocarpus excelsus include its potential to reduce inflammation, improve respiratory health, and exhibit antimicrobial properties, making it a valuable traditional medicine in many African cultures. The bioactive constituents of this plant include flavonoids, terpenoids, and phenolic compounds, which are responsible for its medicinal properties. The most common herbal preparations made with Podocarpus excelsus include a tea, decoction, and infused oil, which are used to treat various ailments, including bronchitis, coughs, and skin conditions."}